
[1]tacit

   TAC'IT, a. [L. tacitus, from taceo, to be silent, that is, to stop, or
   to close. See Tack.] Silent; implied, but not expressed. tacit consent
   is consent by silence, or not interposing an objection. So we say, a
   tacit agreement or covenant of men to live under a particular
   government, when no objection or opposition is made; a tacit surrender
   of a part of our natural rights; a tacit reproach, &c.
